latestPosts.caption:
“But you must eat mambazha curry before you leave!” Marina insisted, when I was in Mumbai. Though we couldn’t meet this time, she, with her characteristic warmth, prepared a simple home-cooked meal and had it sent over for me to savour before my departure.

Tiny golden mangoes nestled in a fragrant coconut curry, sambhar laced with freshly ground podi, a beetroot and beans thoran glistening with coconut oil, her signature chamanthi, and gently steamed rice — a meal as soulful as it was unmistakably Marina.

Need I even introduce @thatthalasserygirl?

From once being hesitant to share her food and wisdom on social media, to now becoming the voice of vegetarian Kerala cuisine — stirring both hearts and the industry with her venture, Ootupura — Marina’s journey has been nothing short of inspiring. And yet, some things remain unchanged. Despite all the acclaim, she remembered my favourite dishes and cooked for me at her home, as we exchanged fond memories of our quiet corner on Gulmohar Cross Road, as always. 

A languid afternoon, a meal steeped in soul, and a heart as full as the belly.

As Marina would say — Annadata Sukhibhava. 🌸🙏🏼

[home chefs, Kerala cuisine, Vegetarian cooking, Indian food, thaali]

Chenna theeyal - the king of all Theeyals 

One of the most cherished and beautiful dishes . Growing up , I remember theeyal being an integral part of a lunch menu, particularly if we had guests coming by. 

Theeyal literally means a burnt dish, which is achieved by slowly roasting coconut into a uniform dark brown colour. Freshly grated luscious coconut works best for this dish. My grandmother was a theeyal expert, and made the dish very much her own. A good theeyal can be deciphered by the look and its aroma, which must reflect the complex balance between flavour, color and texture. For example, it typically must never emit a strong whiff of coriander powder. And one must pay close, patient attention to the aroma while the theeyal cooks, particularly the scent of what is released by the coconut oil while it cooks. Critical also is the quality of coconut used. Examine the outer part of the coconut while purchasing to determine the right freshness for the perfect theeyal. 

Any vegetable can be transformed into a majestic theeyal. But I am particularly partial to the Chenna ( yam ). The well cooked yam tastes extremely delicious in the deeply rich curry. Serve with parottas and you have a feast!

latestPosts.caption:
When ingredients and produce are ripe with flavor and texture, all you need to focus on while cooking is the process of letting them stand out. 

The adage less is more reminds me of kerala vegetarian cuisine. The recipes use few ingredients, requiring more skill and patience in ensuring that the flavors work together and that the vegetables are cooked to just the right texture. 

A dish that calls for this subtlety and skill is Moloshyam. I think I have written about this dish before too. It requires only a drizzle of coconut oil, but the right one opens up the dish like a flower turning towards the sun. On a recent trip to kerala , I spent time understanding how coconut oil is processed and tasted the different varieties of coconut. 

The coconut oil used here is from the Sundried variety from my mother’s farm.The texture, quality and aroma is far superior to any available in the market . A little drizzle of the oil warmed this preparation immensely . The peppercorns again are Thalassery bold ones. Freshly crushed peppercorns added into this preparation is like magic … a good crumble of Guruvayur pappadam over the top to complete the preparation. You don’t need much to feel content .. 

All I needed was a variety of fresh vegetables for this absolutely charming preparation.And ofcourse a Keralite meal is complete when paired with the right variety of rice . I have used unnakalari ( a variety of raw rice mostly used in temple offerings ) . This rice worked perfectly . Also I was mindful of not over cooking this rice as Moloshyam tastes best with a robust texture . 

#keralavegetarian #oonu #homestyle #traditionalkeralafood

latestPosts.caption:
Moloshyam

There is so much to kerala vegetarian cuisine than just the Avial and pachadi and sadya dishes. There are some lesser talked about dishes that feel like a warm hug . One of them is Moloshyam or Mulaku dooshyam. The literal meaning of Mulaku dooshyam means “ chilies are bad”. Which is perhaps why this curry doesn’t use any red chili at all, and instead uses black pepper, adding spice but in a soft and gentle way. Just a simple drizzle of coconut oil at the end is all there is . 

The first time I tried Moloshyam was on a temple visit with my grandmother where we were invited to the home of a temple priest for lunch. We were served a simple meal with red rice, a pumpkin Moloshyam, some tender mango pickle and buttermilk . What I clearly remember is how the family crumbled roasted Pappadam on top of the Moloshyam .  This meal stayed within me for years and I often reminded my grandmother of visiting their home again . 

Today’s meal was about cooking from my memory of that age-old lunch. I drizzled some coconut oil on top of my moloshyam, added a garnish of curry leaves, and crumbled roasted Pappadam on top before settling down to eat with a side of pickle and yoghurt as a way to reminisce that special afternoon. 

Note : Moloshyam can be made with any vegetable . Its base is a lentil which could be tur dal or green moong.

Such is the nourishing energy of food ..

Annadatta Sukhibhava

With each passing year , my learnings and experience with cooking a sadya deepen. This year Onam kickstarted with the collaboration with @suta_bombay . Sarees have been my deepest love and it was surprising to see how my love for sarees and cooking blended so well with collaborations . 

As I always say , cooking a sadya is a divine experience. It’s not only an act of cooking and serving . Years of cooking have taught me things deeper and spiritual about the act of cooking .. this year furthered this understanding. 

Each and every collaboration carried something so deep .. from the suta sarees to the @omo.cafe pop up to the cooking video with @keertidacooks to the large sadya  @grandhyattmumbai and all the other collaborations ..

Onam is the beginning of new . Onam is about abundance in every aspect of living . Onam is about contributing your innate energy to bring joy into other’s lives . This Onam has brought so many deeper lessons to living.. 

Thank you all for giving me yet another divine opportunity to cook , nurture and nourish you all through my cooking . This year has been phenomenal … thank you for trusting and cheering my work ..

Look forward to continue serving you … 

Annadatta Sukhibhava

A good ishtew for me means using the best spices , the best coconut oil and ofcourse ,the best vegetables . So with an array of mushrooms from @shroomery.in , I had to make a kerala ishtew .. paired it with fresh Idiappams .. a hearty meal is what the end result is .. I used an array of mushrooms from king trumpet to oyster to lions mane . Each of them I added at different intervals .. savoured the most umami filled ishtew .. my tummy and heart full … can’t wait to try some Naadan recipes with these delicious mushrooms… 

Annadatta Sukhibhava

The unforgettable Onam Sadhya at the Grand Hyatt Mumbai, featuring the exquisite Onam feast curated by Chef Marina Balakrishnan. Immerse yourself in pure faith, pure festivities, and pure food as we celebrate this vibrant festival with a lavish spread that honors tradition and taste. 

Organic Tattva loved to be a part of this unique culinary experience which was filled with pure love and pure ingredients .

A Taste of Tradition: OMO’s Onam Sadya, curated by Chef Marina Balakrishnan, was a feast for the senses. From Thalassery to your table, a celebration of Kerala’s rich culinary heritage.

Wishing you a joyous and abundant Onam! 🌴

[Chef Marina Balakrishnan, OMO, OMO Tables, Onam, Onam Sadya]

“Right from the time I remember, Onam meant a lot of warmth.” 
Chef Marina Balakrishnan (@thatthalasserygirl), who grew up with her grandmother, thinks back to the wholesome celebrations from her childhood back in Thalassery, Kerala. Festivities were signaled by the bringing out of the large urulis used to make sambar and payasam.

“Every single component that went into Onam — from banana chips to the floral pookalams — would be homemade. I remember my grandmother being ever so particular about what kind of papadam would go into the sadhya banana leaf. She would call our family papadam-maker a month or two in advance and order a lot of it because she knew us kids loved it.”​

Now far away from home in Mumbai, in an attempt at retaining the techniques and traditions she has grown up with, Chef Balakrishnan hosts culinary events across India and internationally.
